Introduction to Queue in Java

Queue is an interface in Java used to store elements in a FIFO (First In, First Out) order.

👉 This means:

the first element added is the first one removed

Example:

Add: 1 → 2 → 3  
Remove: 1 → 2 → 3
Where Queue is used
task processing
messaging systems
scheduling
buffering data
Common Queue Implementations
LinkedList → most simple implementation
PriorityQueue → sorted by priority
ArrayDeque → modern and fast
LinkedList as a Queue

LinkedList can be used as a Queue because it implements the Queue interface.

Creating a Queue
import java.util.Queue;
import java.util.LinkedList;

Queue<String> queue = new LinkedList<>();
Main Queue Methods
add() / offer()
queue.add("Apple");
queue.offer("Banana");

👉 both add elements to the queue

add() → throws exception if fails
offer() → returns false if fails
remove() / poll()
queue.remove();
queue.poll();

👉 remove first element

remove() → throws exception if empty
poll() → returns null if empty
element() / peek()
queue.element();
queue.peek();

👉 get first element (without removing)

element() → exception if empty
peek() → returns null if empty
Example
Queue<Integer> queue = new LinkedList<>();

queue.add(1);
queue.add(2);
queue.add(3);

System.out.println(queue.poll()); // 1
System.out.println(queue.peek()); // 2
Important Features
FIFO order
allows duplicates
allows null (depends on implementation)
not thread-safe
Queue vs Stack
Queue	Stack
FIFO	LIFO
First in → first out	Last in → first out
Performance
add/remove from ends → O(1)
efficient for queue operations
Summary
Queue follows FIFO principle
LinkedList can be used as a Queue
main methods:
offer() / add()
poll() / remove()
peek() / element()
